(xviii)  conduct training and coaching on change management requirements. 

5.  Deliverables and reports. The e-governance specialist will submit a work plan 1 week after his or 
her engagement. He or she will prepare various reports as requested by ADB, including a monitoring and 
evaluation plan of the G2C project and the DRC’s TAMIS project.  

6.  System engineering and network specialist (international, 6 person-months, junior). The 
system engineering and network (SEN) specialist will have a university degree in information technology, 
business administration, engineering, economics, or related fields, preferably at post-graduate level or the 
equivalent. He or she must have at least 8 years of relevant professional work experience in the ICT and 
development field. The specialist will preferably have worked previously in South Asia on international 
development assignments and must have demonstrated experience in successfully managing teams in 
development projects.  The SEN specialist  will help implement component  2 of the TA (enhancing 
government performance using e-governance and citizens’ participation). Specifically, the consultant will 
provide support for the implementation, coordination, and monitoring of the G2C project’s linkage with the 
DRC’s TAMIS. The SEN specialist will 

 (i)  help the e-governance specialist conduct an as-is study and functionality analysis for 
introducing an internally acceptable tax filing system;  
(ii)  help the e-governance specialist review the functional requirements of the TAMIS; 
(iii)  prepare technical requirements for the application software in consultation with the DRC; 
(iv)  assist in preparation of IT infrastructure requirement documents; 
(v)  prepare solution architecture and provide inputs during tender evaluation; 
(vi)  monitor the tendering and evaluation process;  
(vii)  help the DRC coordinate and synchronize the activities of TAMIS implementation; 
(viii)  help the DRC analyze computer training requirements related to the TAMIS; 
(ix)  help the DRC evaluate the change management to be undertaken by the TAMIS 
implementation partner; 
(x)  support the DRC in the design of workshops and provide training on IT applications; 
(xi)  monitor project progress and provide reports on project implementation progress;  
(xii)  help the e-governance specialist review all the deliverables and the performance of the 
TAMIS implementation partner;

  Appendix 3  15 

(i)  conduct an assessment of the implementation risks for the planned activities in each of 
the components of the project; 
(ii)  assess the likelihood, expected severity, and potential impact of the risks; 
(iii)  evaluate  the  technical,  political,  financial,  and  managerial  resources  available  for 
deployment to assist in the formulation and implementation of risk-mitigation measures; 
(iv)  recommend alternatives that the government could take to reduce and manage the risks; 
(v)  prepare a report on suggested land records registration process in Bhutan; 
(vi)  prepare a feasibility study on as-is IT usage and development; 
(vii)  develop regulatory and statutory rules related to land registration; 
(viii)  recommend  institutional  and  organizational  structures  for  enhanced  land  records 
registration; 
(ix)  prepare functional and technical requirements for the land records management system; 
(x)  prepare a road map for conceptualizing a digitized land records management system, 
that would include (a) digitizing text data and cadastral paper maps, (b) linking the land 
records management system with other G2C modules, and (c) developing a web-based 
database of land records; 
(xi)  conduct capacity development and training for related stakeholders; and 
(xii)  do other related tasks, as required by ADB and the government. 

15.  Deliverables and reports. The PSM specialist will prepare and submit the following reports: (i) an 
inception assessment of project implementation risks, with recommendations of risk-mitigation measures; 
(ii) a midterm review of project implementation risks and the results of risk-mitigation measures; and (iii) a 
final report of project implementation risks with a view to project sustainability. The specialist will also 
conduct at least three change management workshops with project implementers and stakeholders. 

16.  Project  management  specialist  (national,  12  person-months).  The  project  management 
specialist will have graduate degree in management, economics, or a relevant discipline. With at least 5 
years of experience, the project management specialist must have demonstrated successful project 
management experience of international development projects. He or she must also have strong written 
and verbal communications skills. The objective of this position is to provide regular onsite management 
support to the government and the consulting firm in the implementation of the four components of the TA. 
The specialist will provide weekly reports to ADB on issues of implementation, which will highlight 
concerns and problems as they arise as well as report on successful completion of project milestones. 
The PM specialist will help the various TA consultants coordinate their schedules, set up meetings, and 
prepare action plans agreed upon in meetings. The project management specialist will 

(i)  help  the  executing  agency  project  director  supervise  the  implementation  of  the  TA 
components; 
(ii)  provide logistical and administrative support to the component consultants; 
(iii)  organize regular steering committee meetings and prepare summaries and action points 
from each meeting; 
(iv)  serve as liaison between the government, the consulting firm, and ADB; 
(v)  prepare and submit weekly, monthly, and quarterly reports to ADB; and 
(vi)  provide support to ADB and government review missions. 

17.  Deliverables and reports. The project manager will submit brief weekly reports to the steering 
committee and ADB that will highlight the results of the previous week’s activities, outline the tasks in the 
coming  week  and  beyond,  discuss  potential  issues,  and  recommend  action  to  be  taken  by  the 
government and ADB. He or she will report to the project director at the Ministry of Finance and the 
project officer at ADB.
